definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + 5'-dephosphopolynucleotide -eq- ADP + 5'-phosphopolynucleotide. The polynucleotide may be DNA or RNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GTP + 5'-dephosphopolynucleotide -eq- GDP + 5'-phosphopolynucleotide. The polynucleotide may be DNA or RNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + 5'-dephospho-RNA -eq- ADP + 5'-phospho-RNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GTP + 5'-dephospho-DNA -eq- GDP + 5'-phospho-DNA.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with xanthophylls, any of several neutral yellow to orange carotenoid pigments containing oxygen.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with ethylene (C2-H4, ethene), a simple hydrocarbon gas that can function in plants as a growth regulator.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-methyl-6-phytyl-1,4-benzoquinone + S-adenosyl-methionine -eq- 2,3-dimethyl-6-phytyl-1,4-benzoquinone + S-adenosyl-homocysteine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2-methyl-6-solanyl-1,4-benzoquinone + S-adenosyl-methionine -eq- 2,3-dimethyl-6-solanyl-1,4-benzoquinone + S-adenosyl-homocysteine.

Catalysis of the reaction -  red chlorophyll catabolite + reduced ferredoxin + 2 H+ -eq- primary fluorescent catabolite + oxidized ferredoxin. This reaction is the reduction of the C20|C1 double bond in the pyrrole system of red chlorophyll catabolite (RCC) to a colorless tetrapyrrole (pFCC) with a strong blue fluorescence.
Catalysis of the reaction -  divinyl protochlorophyllide a + NADPH + H+ -eq- monovinyl protochlorophyllide a + NADP+.

Catalysis of the reaction -  (E)-4-hydroxy-3-methylbut-2-en-1-yl diphosphate + NAD(P)H + H+ -eq- isopentenyl diphosphate + NAD(P)+ + H2O. Note that (E)-4-hydroxy-3-methylbut-2-en-1-yl diphosphate is an alternative name for 1-hydroxy-2-methyl-2-(E)-butenyl 4-diphosphate.
Catalysis of the cyclization of 3(S)-oxidosqualene to (3S,13S,14R)-malabarica-8,17,21-trien-3-ol (thalianol).
Catalysis of the reaction -  methyl-dCpdG DNA + H2O -eq- dCpdG DNA + methanol. This reaction is the hydrolytic removal of the methyl group on the 5 position of cytosine in DNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UTP + a monosaccharide 1-phosphate -eq- diphosphate + UDP-monosaccharide.

label.value: indole acetic acid carboxyl methyltransferase activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  indole acetic acid + S-adenosyl-methionine -eq- methyl indole acetic acid ester + S-adenosyl-homocysteine.
Catalysis of the isomerization of 3,5-dienoyl-CoA to 2,4-dienoyl-CoA.
Catalysis of the transfer of a mannose residue to an oligosaccharide, forming an alpha-(1--gt-4) linkage.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + [phospho-alpha-glucan] + H2O -eq- AMP + O-phospho-[phospho-alpha-glucan] + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  mannan(n) + GDP-mannose -eq- mannan(n+1) + GDP. This reaction is the formation of the beta-(1--gt-4)-linked mannan backbone in substrates such as galactomannan.
Catalysis of the reaction -  inositol tetrakisphosphate + ATP -eq- inositol pentakisphosphate + ADP.
Catalysis of the reaction -  inositol trisphosphate + ATP -eq- inositol tetrakisphosphate + ADP.

Catalysis of the reaction -  ent-kaurenoate + NADPH + O2 -eq- ent-7-alpha-hydroxykaurenoate + NADP+ + H2O. This is the first of three successive reactions resulting in the oxidation of ent-kaurenoate (ent-kaurenoic acid) to gibberellin 12 (GA12).

Catalysis of the reaction -  ent-7-alpha-hydroxykaurenoate + NADPH + H+ + O2 -eq- gibberellin 12-aldehyde + NADP+ + 2 H2O. This is the second of three successive reactions resulting in the oxidation of ent-kaurenoate (ent-kaurenoic acid) to gibberellin 12 (GA12).

Catalysis of the reaction -  gibberellin 12-aldehyde + NADPH + H+ + O2 -eq- gibberellin 12 + NADP+ + H2O. This is the third of three successive reactions resulting in the oxidation of ent-kaurenoate (ent-kaurenoic acid) to gibberellin 12 (GA12).
Catalysis of the reaction -  all-trans-13,14-dihydroretinol + A -eq- all-trans-retinol + AH(2). Note that this reaction has only been observed to occur in the opposite direction.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a misfolded protein.
Catalysis of the reaction -  phosphatidylinositol-3,4-bisphosphate + H2O -eq- phosphatidylinositol-4-phosphate + phosphate.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a glycolipid, any compound containing one or more monosaccharide residues bound by a glycosidic linkage to a hydrophobic group such as an acylglycerol, a sphingoid, a ceramide (N-acylsphingoid) or a prenyl phosphate.

Catalysis of the reaction -  histone H3 N6-methyl-L-lysine (position 36) + alpha-ketoglutarate + O2 -eq- succinate + CO2 + formaldehyde + lysine. This reaction is the removal of a methyl group from lysine at position 36 of the histone H3 protein.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with methotrexate, an antineoplastic antimetabolite with immunosuppressant properties. It is an inhibitor of tetrahydrofolate reductase and prevents the formation of tetrahydrofolate, necessary for synthesis of thymidylate, an essential component of DNA.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with dihydrofolic acid, a folic acid in which the bicyclic pteridine structure is in the dihydro, partially reduced form -  they are intermediates in folate metabolism and are reduced to their tetrahydro, reduced forms.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with Hsp90 proteins, any of a group of heat shock proteins around 90kDa in size.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with G-quadruplex DNA structures, in which groups of four guanines adopt a flat, cyclic Hoogsteen hydrogen-bonding arrangement known as a guanine tetrad. The stacking of guanine tetrads results in G-quadruplex DNA structures. G-quadruplex DNA can form under physiological conditions from some G-rich sequences, such as those found in telomeres, immunoglobulin switch regions, gene promoters, fragile X repeats, and the dimerization domain in the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) genome.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-(hydroxymethyl)glutathione + NAD(P)+ -eq- S-formylglutathione + NAD(P)H + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-(hydroxymethyl)glutathione -eq- formaldehyde + glutathione.
Catalysis of the sequential cleavage of mononucleotides from a free 5' terminus of a double-stranded DNA molecule.
Catalysis of the reaction -  3-hydroxypropenoate -eq- propynoate + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction -  H2 + 2-(2,3-dihydropentaprenyloxy)phenazine -eq- 2-dihydropentaprenyloxyphenazine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  coenzyme B + coenzyme M + methanophenazine -eq- N-{7-[(2-sulfoethyl)dithio]heptanoyl}-3-O-phospho-L-threonine + dihydromethanophenazine.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with granulocyte colony-stimulating factor, G-CSF.
Catalysis of the reaction -  2 R'-SH + ROOH -eq- R'-S-S-R' + H2O + ROH.
Catalysis of the reaction -  4 L-glutamine + adenosylcob(III)yrinate a,c-diamide + 4 ATP + 4 H(2)O -eq- 4 L-glutamate + adenosylcobyrate + 4 ADP + 8 H(+) + 4 phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate + cholesterol -eq- adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate + cholesterol sulfate.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a light intermediate chain of the dynein complex.

Enables the directed movement of lysophospholipids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. A lysophospholipid is a phospholipid that lacks one of its fatty acyl chains -  it is an intermediate formed during digestion of dietary and biliary phospholipids.
Catalysis of the transfer of the iron chelate iron-nicotianamine (Fe-NA) from one side of a membrane to the other.

Catalysis of the transfer of a copper chelate from one side of a membrane to the other. A copper chelate is a heterocyclic compound having a metal ion attached by coordinate bonds to at least two nonmetal ions.
Catalysis of the transfer of the copper chelate copper-nicotianamine (Cu-NA) from one side of a membrane to the other.
Catalysis of the reaction -  coproporphyrinogen III + 2 S-adenosyl-L-methionine -eq- protoporphyrinogen IX + 2 CO2 + 2 L-methionine + 2 5'-deoxyadenosine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-2-hydroxyglutarate + acceptor -eq- 2-oxoglutarate + reduced acceptor.
